---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Project Scaffolding"
  description="Create a new project from a starter template with shuttle new"
  section="Getting Started"
>
  <p>
    <code>shuttle new</code> scaffolds a new application from an opinionated starter template.
    It generates a <code>shuttle.yml</code>, a production-ready <code>Dockerfile</code>,
    a <code>.dockerignore</code>, and optionally CI workflow files — so you can go from zero
    to a deployable app in under a minute.
  </p>

  <h2>Usage</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle new &lt;framework&gt; &lt;app-name&gt; [options]</code></pre>

  <h3>Available frameworks</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Framework</th>
        <th>Command</th>
        <th>Notes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Laravel</td>
        <td><code>shuttle new laravel my-app</code></td>
        <td>PHP 8.3, Octane, Horizon optional</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Symfony</td>
        <td><code>shuttle new symfony my-app</code></td>
        <td>PHP 8.3, Messenger optional</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>More frameworks (Next.js, Django, Rails) are planned for future releases.</p>

  <h2>Interactive prompts</h2>
  <p>
    Running <code>shuttle new laravel my-app</code> starts an interactive wizard that asks:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Server address</strong> — e.g. <code>deploy@203.0.113.10</code></li>
    <li><strong>Domain</strong> — e.g. <code>my-app.example.com</code></li>
    <li><strong>Database</strong> — Postgres, MySQL, MariaDB, or none</li>
    <li><strong>Cache / queue driver</strong> — Redis or none</li>
    <li><strong>Queue worker</strong> — Horizon (Laravel) or Messenger (Symfony)</li>
    <li><strong>Mail catcher</strong> — Mailpit for local dev / staging</li>
    <li><strong>Deploy strategy</strong> — blue-green or rolling</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Generated files</h2>
  <p>After running <code>shuttle new laravel my-app</code>, the following files are created inside <code>my-app/</code>:</p>
  <pre><code class="language-text">my-app/
├── shuttle.yml          # deployment configuration
├── Dockerfile           # production-optimised multi-stage build
├── .dockerignore        # excludes dev dependencies, tests, etc.
└── .github/
    └── workflows/
        └── deploy.yml   # GitHub Actions workflow (if selected)</code></pre>

  <h2>Example: Laravel with Postgres and Redis</h2>
  <p>The following is the <code>shuttle.yml</code> generated for a Laravel app with Postgres, Redis, and Horizon:</p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">app: my-app
domain: my-app.example.com
server: deploy@203.0.113.10

build:
  context: .
  dockerfile: Dockerfile

deploy:
  strategy: blue-green
  timeout: 120
  retain: 5
  auto_rollback: true
  hooks:
    post_deploy:
      - php artisan migrate --force

services:
  web:
    port: 8000
    healthcheck:
      path: /up
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 6
  horizon:
    command: php artisan horizon
    # no port — not exposed via proxy

accessories:
  postgres:
    preset: postgres
    env:
      POSTGRES_DB: my_app_production
      POSTGRES_USER: my_app
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: !secret DB_PASSWORD
  redis:
    preset: redis

env:
  clear:
    APP_ENV: production
    APP_URL: https://my-app.example.com
    DB_CONNECTION: pgsql
    DB_HOST: localhost
    DB_PORT: "5432"
    DB_DATABASE: my_app_production
    DB_USERNAME: my_app
    CACHE_DRIVER: redis
    QUEUE_CONNECTION: redis
    SESSION_DRIVER: redis
  secret:
    - APP_KEY
    - DB_PASSWORD

secrets:
  file: .shuttle.secrets

proxy:
  driver: caddy
  ssl: true</code></pre>

  <h2>CI flag — skip interactive prompts</h2>
  <p>
    Use <code>--yes</code> (or <code>-y</code>) to accept all defaults without interactive
    prompts. This is useful in scripts and CI pipelines:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle new laravel my-app \
  --server deploy@203.0.113.10 \
  --domain my-app.example.com \
  --database postgres \
  --redis \
  --yes</code></pre>

  <h2>Dockerfile</h2>
  <p>
    The generated <code>Dockerfile</code> uses a multi-stage build optimised for production.
    For Laravel it uses <a href="https://serversideup.net/open-source/docker-php/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">serversideup/php</a>
    as the base image, pre-installs Composer dependencies with <code>--no-dev</code>, and
    runs PHP-FPM with FrankenPHP or Octane depending on your selection.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can customise the generated <code>Dockerfile</code> freely — Shuttle treats it as
    a regular Docker build context and does not impose any constraints on the image contents.
  </p>

